---
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro'
import SiteNav from '../components/SiteNav.astro'
import '../styles/global.css'

const suggestionsSheetUrl = 'https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1fpTkJmAByHD-Xsj54zGI23ofJhP-GWw1eDeg3Nny0oo/edit?gid=0#gid=0'
---

<html lang="en-GB">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width" />
    <title>Suggest a source — Civic Signals</title>
  </head>

  <body>
    <main class="page">
      <header class="masthead">
        <p class="site-label">Civic Signals</p>

        <h1>Suggest a source</h1>

        <p class="lede">
          Help Civic Signals find strong public sources relevant to UK digital government and digital delivery.
        </p>

        <SiteNav current="" />
      </header>

      <section class="suggest-source" aria-labelledby="suggest-source-heading">
        <h2 id="suggest-source-heading">Add a source suggestion</h2>

        <p>
          Civic Signals is built from public sources that help people working in and around UK digital government keep up with the wider ecosystem and improve the products and services they build.
        </p>

        <p>
          Suggested sources are reviewed before they are added. A source does not need to publish often to be useful. Rare, strong material is welcome if it is relevant.
        </p>

        <p>
          You do not need a GitHub account. Add your suggestion to the public spreadsheet.
        </p>

        <p class="suggest-source__action">
          <a class="button-link" href={suggestionsSheetUrl}>Open the source suggestions spreadsheet</a>
        </p>

        <h2>What to add</h2>

        <p>
          Add as much as you know. The source URL and why the source is useful are the most important fields.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Source name</li>
          <li>Source URL</li>
          <li>Feed URL, if you know it</li>
          <li>Source type</li>
          <li>Relevance area</li>
          <li>Whether it is UK-focused or international context relevant to the UK</li>
          <li>Why this source is useful</li>
          <li>Your name or contact details, if you want to include them</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Useful sources</h2>

        <p>
          Civic Signals is interested in sources that help people understand digital government, public services, digital delivery, product practice, service design, user research, content design, civic technology, public-sector reform and professional practice.
        </p>

        <p>
          Sources can be about the business of government, but they can also be about creating excellent products and services: product strategy, discovery, delivery, outcomes, continuous learning, design quality and operating models.
        </p>

        <p>
          International sources are welcome when they help UK practitioners understand good practice, standards, comparable approaches or where the bar is moving.
        </p>

        <h2>Review process</h2>

        <p>
          Suggestions start with the status <strong>New</strong>. They may later be marked as in review, accepted, not included or needing more information.
        </p>

        <p>
          Accepted sources are added to Civic Signals through the normal review process, rather than being added automatically from the spreadsheet.
        </p>
      </section>

      <SiteFooter />
    </main>
  </body>
</html>

<style>
  .suggest-source {
    max-width: 720px;
  }

  .suggest-source__action {
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .button-link {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.65rem 0.9rem;
    background: #00703c;
    color: #ffffff;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .button-link:hover {
    background: #005a30;
  }

  .button-link:focus {
    outline: 3px solid #ffdd00;
    outline-offset: 0;
    background: #ffdd00;
    color: #000000;
  }
</style>
